Modify parser to match new command output

this platformAdaptor was originally implemented.  Modify the
parsing logic to accept the new output format.

commits.commitMessage:
[AVMS] Support +WDSI notification and handle +WDSR=4 for local update

Per requirement from Iskraemeco customer, we will support local update +WDSD.
We need to support +WDSI notifications and handle +WDSR=4 for local update.

Resolves: LE-16556 LE-16557
Related: QTI9X07TX-3884 QTI9X07TX-3885
Change-Id: I1ecadf2457dde80f8ee0aab584418c3438d8e9b8
Signed-off-by: Tien Tra <TTra@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: [AVMS] Support +WDSI notification and handle +WDSR=4 for local update

commits.commitMessage:
Fix the bug that cannot quit data mode when running +GNSSNMEA

The issue is when registering the Data Port Rx and Tx functions via
serialMngrbind2SerialPortApi(), a volatile fd handle was used to
register as appCookie which will be stored in FW and passed through
to the callback as a parameter. And when FW calls the registered
callback function, DataPortRxFunc(), this fd handle might be
already invalid if the data port has been closed previously. This
causes the handle not pointing to the correct device and thus
cannot quit from data mode.

This patch updates to store the static AT device pointer as
appCookie and search the correct data port device in
DeviceObjRegistry via data device name to send POLLIN event.

Resolves: LE-16424
Change-Id: I109aad789ea5aab834b68c73b9ca0bdf0afd43c6
commits.subject: Fix the bug that cannot quit data mode when running +GNSSNMEA

commits.commitMessage:
Fix CMUX port open/close handling

First, ensure that the AT command session pointer in the device object
is set back to NULL when a port is closed, as checking this for NULL is
used to determine if it needs to be opened again later.

Second, fix the string comparison used when searching for devices, as
the existing logic was erroneously succeeding for strings that were
exact prefixes of the expected result.

Finally, add assertions to ensure that the underlying logical port IDs
are always consistent between the device object and the AT command
session object.

Resolves: LE-16402
Change-Id: Ib7014dd1802239cf096d42404f2d7a5224517e56
commits.subject: Fix CMUX port open/close handling

commits.commitMessage:
Correct active PDN counting code

The code currently considers it a failure if the modem reports
fewer than the number of supported PDNs.  Modify to finish counting
immediately once all PDNs reported by the modem have been processed,
without considering it an error.

Resolves: LE-16142
Change-Id: Ia232e5ba1cfc814d055789e3b66293176b610c51
commits.subject: Correct active PDN counting code

commits.commitMessage:
Module cannot fix location and URC +GNSSEV: 3,3 is not returned

Device fails to parse NMEA sentences correctly because there is
a change in the NMEA sentence on RK3.2, last quotation mark is omitted.

Fixed the issue by adding a check to see if there is a quotation mark
in the NMEA sentence before removing it.

Resolves: LE-16186
Signed-off-by: Jagadeesh Muddana <JMuddana@sierrawireless.com>
Change-Id: I0554c16b37db42a36ccd393cb41d1efaf3898e7d
commits.subject: Module cannot fix location and URC +GNSSEV: 3,3 is not returned

commits.commitMessage:
Extended error code setting persistence on MCU

These changes:

- Add three new platformAdaptor functions to the pa_atProxy file:
pa_atProxy_EnableExtendedErrorCodes(),
pa_atProxy_DisableExtendedErrorCodes(),
pa_atProxy_GetExtendedErrorCodes().

For the MAP PA, these are implemented using the original logic
that relies on a static/local variable, ErrorCodeMode.

For the MCU PA, these are implemented using the new MCU filesystem
to store and persist this data in flash.

- Remove the KSWIREADY AT command support.

Resolves: LE-15989
Change-Id: I2102e2db4084b4379f03e60581f958d106963f02
commits.subject: Extended error code setting persistence on MCU

comments.message: This function looks can be removed, instead we can directly call pa_atProxy_DisableExtendedErrorCodes(), the same to le_atServer_EnableExtendedErrorCodes() which shall directly call pa function as well.
I think the convention for global variable is capitalizing the first character.
can we use a more intuitive way to set the expectedReadyCount, for example, to check if the overlay is applied (atIp will not run)?

As discussed, this is the best logic we have right now for determining this.   This check can only be done at runtime (dynamically) and cannot be determined when building the image.  Instead, I have added a note to alert developers that this logic may need tweaking in the future if further apps also require to use the KSWIREADY event.
Sorry, I forgot to ask, is this sleep(2) needed? If yes, why 2 seconds,is the number obtained based on some testing or FW team?

Good question.  It is still needed in order to ensure that the FW is initialized upon start-up.   Without it, there is a risk of the ATC Command registration completing before the FW is ready to receive a SIG_ATCMD_READY.  It was found that 2 seconds gave sufficient buffer to ensure that the system was in a ready state.
OK, does FW team have a long-term solution for this? And, I think it's better to add comment to mention why here, and/or the long-term solution.

Hi Lars, we might need a more robust solution for this problem. It must have been before that atIp init was taking long enough we didn't see the ATC error.

FW boot time can significantly increase depending on flash activity (we have seen increases of >1s on RK2.1.2 branch when a flash sector erase happens and blocks all file system reads). I worry that if we see an unexpected boot time, it will expose persistence issues here and maybe elsewhere too.

I have removed the 2 second sleep from the Legato changes.  In the meantime, Ross Gardner will include this as part of the work for https://issues.sierrawireless.com/browse/ALT1250-4129, to investigate why the FW is unable to properly handle the event signal if generated early in the boot-up sequence.
Same typos exist in other commit messages in this topic.

Still there.

This is the danger of editing commits directly on Gerrit.  The next patch upload wipes out the previous changes.  It's generally better to amend locally and re-upload.
I'm confused.  If ATIP is active, then the AT Proxy is disabled, but this is in pa_atProxy.c....

This code is running on the MAP and needs to work in both Octave (AT app only) and ATIP (both AT and ATIP apps running) modes.   The idea behind the logic here is that we need to identify how many "AT+KSWIREADY" commands will be registered, and for this I was basing it on the RunGroup.   If the RunGroup is set to 1, indicating the the ATIP app is running, then we will expect two registrations (AT + ATIP, otherwise just one (AT).
This has been moved into the ready service file, named source.c, and no longer requires using the RunGroup.
This description and function name were copied and pasted at some point, and aren't accurate to this file.
No, this is correct.   This is the original description for this function, which is still largely the intact and doing the same as it did previously.

What I mean is that this name was never correct for the file pa_atProxy.c, as it was clearly copied with both the description and name from le_atServer_alt1250.c at some time in the past.  Not in scope for this patch, however.
Can we remove it and furthermore, if AT+KSWIREADY is no longer needed, may be remove it completely for all platforms, or please add comment for this empty "else if" statement.
I'm not prepared to remove the KSWIREADY entirely at this point in time, so I've added a comment instead.
What purpose does keeping it serve?
I'm just worry that it is used by another platform or product (ex. ThreadX).

I have checked with Tom and he does not believe that the SIG_ATCMD_READY event is needed or required for Threadx.   If this is the case, then we may be able to get rid the KSWIREADY altogether and make the code a little cleaner.

Actually, the bigger issue we removing this is that tis is still required for the non-AT Proxy builds that use the original atServer implementation.   I think it should be dealt with separately from this.
Isn't this function only for command registration in the AT proxy and only for HL78?  Why would this file even be compiled in a non AT proxy case?

This file is for the AT Proxy case only.   The issue I'm thinking of is really with the AT and ATIP components, which try to register the KSWIREADY command.  Do we still need the KSWIREADY to work in the non-AT Proxy case?

One way to solve this is to wrap the KSWIREADY code in the AT and ATIP with the MK_CONFIG_ATSERVER_LITE macro so that they can still be built if this has been disabled.   Otherwise, we will need to remove it from the original atServer implementation as well.
Removed this and the KSWIREADY AT command registration from the Command Registry and the AT and ATIP apps.

commits.commitMessage:
HAccuracy & vAccuracy are not reported correctly by Positioning service

Current implementation gets the hAccuracy & vAccuracy information
from the GPGST NMEA sentence, which is not correct. So updated the
implementation to take the accuracy information from the proprietary
NMEA sentence PSIDX.

Resolves: LE-16063
Related: HYB-323
Signed-off-by: Jagadeesh Muddana <JMuddana@sierrawireless.com>
Change-Id: I67fac4360b985b62c74abe65711367b654f571db
commits.subject: HAccuracy & vAccuracy are not reported correctly by Positioning service

commits.commitMessage:
Provide PSM configuration API

Add PA lpt API that will allow users to configure PSM parameters.

Resolves: LE-15950
Change-Id: I8761fd523b7ea9727ff99046622c915691e7e2b9
commits.subject: Provide PSM configuration API

comments.message:
I always find using variants of strlen to detect empty strings to be overkill.  A single equality test is sufficient:

    pRau[0] != '\0'

I won't block the review over it, though.
Ok, with this patch, but see my comment on Legato patch, which would imply an API change here.
I think this name is confusing, as it sounds to me like it is converting from a string to an int.  Maybe call it Uint8ToBinaryStr() instead?

Should not activate PSM mode as a side-effect.  If values cannot be set without activating PSM mode, should either just store internally for next time PSM is activated, or return an error if PSM is not active.

If PSM parameters are set, then PSM is deactivated and re-activated, will PSM parameters be preserved?

I've gone with LE_NOT_POSSIBLE if the mode is set to 0. 

PSM parameters should be preserved however there is a bug right now when rebooting https://issues.sierrawireless.com/browse/HYB-315

I see this a lot in our code, replacing one failure code from a function with a fixed one.
@Keith, are you a fan of this pattern? It always annoyed me when coding that codes got lost because they weren't percolated up.
Our coding standard is capital initial letter for static functions like this.

commits.commitMessage:
[LE-15446] AT+KCELL=0 does not return neighbour cells while RAT is 2G

Issue:
Parsing of the %CGED response used an incorrectly hardcoded
number of lines to find 2G neighbour cell data. This resulted in the
neighbour cell lines being skipped over.

Solution:
Parsing of the %CGED response now compares intermediate
responses with the expected start of a neighbour cell line.

Relates: LE-15446
Resolves: LE-15891
Change-Id: I6bf5a9b1ee7ae1cd912d10a2bc0e434cc08eb7f9
Signed-off-by: Grayson Halliday <Ghalliday@sierrawireless.com>
(cherry picked from commit c918d3a55bd42f016e8ce920205822818556996a)
commits.subject: [LE-15446] AT+KCELL=0 does not return neighbour cells while RAT is 2G

commits.commitMessage:
Extend AT Proxy to enable support for both AT and Data modes

- These changes:

1. Add Data Port device management in the file atProxyDevice.c

2. Implement the functions pa_portService_SetDataMode()
and pa_portService_SetCommandMode(), using the infrastructure
added by the file atProxyDevice.c

3. Create a Port Device reference for each device entry

4. Moves common Port Service related code out of the PA
and into the AT Proxy Port Service.

Resolves: LE-15898
Change-Id: I09051d3d09668e178c6e0b98b6af3323072ae3b4
commits.subject: Extend AT Proxy to enable support for both AT and Data modes

comments.message: since command[] is shared between AT and Data mode, maybe better to use a common name, such as buff[].

looks like we can avoid this for loop, because le_atProxy_StaticDataPort has a member of fd_DeviceObj_t to compare/check with fhPtr->devicePtr. Try something like this:

struct le_atProxy_StaticDataPort* dataPort = CONTAINER_OF(fhPtr->devicePtr, struct le_atProxy_StaticDataPort, deviceObj);
strlen may still have overflow issue, maybe sizeof()?

Vincent, the trouble is what do we use for sizeof()?   Both AtDeviceRegistry[i].at.name and portName are const char* that have been statically declared.    It is not clear to me what sizeof() I should use.

I will leave as is.
Same issue as previously discussed about using sizeof().  Will leave as is.

before or during closing AT session, do we have to make sure that it is inactive? maybe we shall check this inside atProxyCmdHandler_CloseSession() and also flush URCs (we can call atProxyCmdHandler_complete()), else it might have memory leak.
Move into separate array in the atProxyDevice file.

No, on further inspection this cannot be moved into the common structure because both the 'at' and 'data' structures need to define unique logicalPortIds.   They cannot share the same logicalPortId.

Leaving as is.
Move into the AT Proxy device file.
Move to AT Proxy device file.
Move to AT Proxy Port Service.
Move to common code, if possible.
See if this can be moved into common code as well.
The Port Device Reference Map will remain in the PA.
the code seems not opening AT command ports.
Again, these AT Proxy Port Service functions have been added based on yesterday's review meeting to hold common code.  I do not plan on removing them.
the following code seems having no such action.
One minor commenting issue, but otherwise looks good.
Copy/paste error?  This code is just searching for the matching name.

commits.commitMessage:
Call atProxy command handler by queuing to atProxy thread

- When command is forwarded from altair, it calls our callback in
  altair thread (non-legato thread), which will cause atProxy not
  running correctly. So queuing the function to atProxy thread solves
  this issue.

- Also optimize the PA initialization to directly call altair AT
  server initialization function and port initialization function,
  instead of queuing them to thread.

Resolves: LE-15835
Change-Id: I37cc39c7258389185699af9ed9e211a712e9ca7d
commits.subject: Call atProxy command handler by queuing to atProxy thread

commits.commitMessage:
Incorporate le_port.api support for data mode into atProxy

These changes:

1. Add the new MAP PA for the AT Proxy, to enable the atService.

2. Add support for hosting the le_port.api in the AT Proxy.

3. Add a new MAP PA for the AT Proxy Port Service.

4. Implement the le_port_Request, le_port_Release, le_port_GetPortReference
APIs using the pa_portService.

Resolves: LE-15679 LE-15681 LE-15772
Change-Id: I210f1e6d4aacbf50311cf497a7054a4695dfb2d2
commits.subject: Incorporate le_port.api support for data mode into atProxy

comments.message: Please also mention LE-15772, since this patch has included the original work from https://gerrit.legato/c/Legato/platformAdaptor/altair/+/71517, which I can abandon some time later.
move these comments to parameter list to be consistent with others.
I know this is from existing atService code, but to comply with current convention, it's better to rename to FormatAtCommandTermination or so.

I know this function is queued in existing atServer code, but it is better to not queue it, since any atSwi, atIp commands registration needs to be executed after this, which causes the registration of these commands also need to be queued. I am working on the possibility to not queue it, and will sync up with you.
Again, I think you should change this when you are making the necessary changes for registering/supporting the AT SWI commands.
would you add some comments to explain these macros, enums, and the architecture of the device layer (originally Json content).
move these to before any function definition
move to above, where has other struct definitions.
this function doesn't need to be queued.
I think this should be modified as part of your changes for registering ATSWI commands instead, when we have the ability to test this more extensively.
not a big issue, since deviceName is a hard-written const char*. But still strlen potentially has a stack overflow problem when there's no NULL at the end of the string.
I think it is fine as is, because these will be NULL-terminated.

I wonder if we can move these code to a common function, since this logic/code is the same among all three places, and will be the same if we have new instance of atProxy (such as RC76):
1. Here
2. InitPortServiceAlt1250 in pa_port.c
3. MCU.

Good point, but I think we should leave as is until the dust has settles a bit more.   More changes are expected as we bring in support for le_port_SetDataMode and le_port_SetCommandMode, so we may want to wait until this is complete before doing this.
OK, although I think this abstraction is relatively independent and can be invoked by new implemented APIs if needed.
Maybe add a NULL check for atServerDevRef, and return LE_BAD_PARAMETER if NULL.

Please also add the two tickets to "Resolves:" section:
1. LE-15681 , as this patch does the removal of Json content parsing.
2. LE-15772, since this patch has included the original work from https://gerrit.legato/c/Legato/platformAdaptor/altair/+/71517, which I can abandon once this patch is merged.
would you add some comments to explain these macros, enums, and the architecture of the device layer (originally Json content)?
this is a structure, won't need [IN].
just a minor suggestion, maybe combine them into one if check and LE_ERROR("Invalid parameters!"), but OK with current.
This enum only has one value and looks not used throughout the PA, wonder if it is not really needed and can be removed?
Subject is a bit misleading.  I think it should be more like "Incorporate le_port.api support for data mode into atProxy."

Agreed.   Although, this is coming from the description of the ticket itself, LE-15679.   I'm inclined to leave it as is, as  the body of the commit message does elaborate on this more,

"2. Add support for hosting the le_port.api in the AT Proxy."
Doesn't need to be done now, but with the AT proxy, I think the need for AT+KSWIREADY is obviated.  This ties in to ATSWI-103 as well.
This should have at least at TODO or FIXME describing why it is disabled/what needs to be done to enable it, or it should be removed.

Patch Set 1: Cherry Picked from branch uLegato-merge.1.

The following files contain Git conflicts:
* components/le_pa_alt1250/pa_sim.c

commits.commitMessage:
[HL78xx] STK related pa_sim support

Add support for STK related Legato objects

le_sim_SendApdu
le_sim_SendCommand
le_sim_AddSimToolkitEventHandler
le_sim_RemoveSimToolkitEventHandler
le_sim_OpenLogicalChannel
le_sim_CloseLogicalChannel
le_sim_SetPower

Also slightly modified le_sim_GetICCID to use native
Altair AT cmd AT%CCID instead of overloaded command
AT+CCID which will eventually contain eUICC EID string.

Resolves: LE-14585
Change-Id: Ida2562acfa81ada6cf6a44585a4ddbfe6183b25d
Signed-off-by: Yonatan Indrajaya <yindrajaya@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: [HL78xx] STK related pa_sim support
